Full MCP stack (Sequential + Memory + Files + Git)

One-command PowerShell installer script

Codex-ready agent prompt (enterprise-grade)

Complete mcp.json optimized for dev automation

AI Operating System layout (agent-first architecture)

State which direction you want to operationalize next, and I will align the deployment blueprint accordingly.

im using codex
Thought for 12s

If you‚Äôre using OpenAI Codex (CLI / IDE extension), you do not configure MCP via mcp.json. Codex manages MCP in ~/.codex/config.toml and provides a dedicated codex mcp command set.

1) Prereqs

Sequential Thinking MCP is typically run via Node + npx.

node -v
npx -v


If those fail, install Node.js LTS first. (Codex MCP supports both CLI and IDE clients using the same config.)

2) Add Sequential Thinking MCP to Codex (recommended path)

Use the Codex MCP CLI to register a STDIO server (local process):

codex mcp add sequential-thinking -- npx -y @modelcontextprotocol/server-sequential-thinking


This follows Codex‚Äôs required pattern:

codex mcp add <server-name> -- <stdio server-command>


Verify it‚Äôs onboarded:

codex mcp list


Then in the Codex TUI, you can use:

/mcp


to confirm it is active.

3) Alternative: Configure directly in ~/.codex/config.toml

Create the file if it doesn‚Äôt exist:

macOS/Linux:

mkdir -p ~/.codex


Windows (PowerShell):

mkdir $HOME\.codex -Force


Add this block:

[mcp_servers.sequential-thinking]
command = "npx"
args = ["-y", "@modelcontextprotocol/server-sequential-thinking"]


Codex supports MCP server config entries under [mcp_servers.<name>], including command, args, and optional env, cwd, etc.

4) Operational troubleshooting (high-frequency issues)
A) npx not found / Node not installed

Install Node.js LTS and reopen your terminal. (This is the dominant root cause on fresh Windows environments.)

B) MCP server added but not visible

Codex CLI and IDE extension share ~/.codex/config.toml. Restart the client after changes.

C) Prefer ‚Äúno global installs‚Äù

Using npx -y ... is the cleanest operational model (no global npm state drift). This is also how Codex docs illustrate MCP server setup (example shown with Context7).

5) Quick sanity test (in Codex)

Ask Codex to solve something that benefits from explicit step sequencing (e.g., ‚Äúbreak into steps, then execute‚Äù). If the toolchain is correctly wired, you‚Äôll see MCP tool usage in the run.

If you tell me your environment (Windows host vs Windows Sandbox vs WSL), I can provide a single copy-paste bootstrap script (PowerShell or bash) that: installs Node (if needed), registers sequential-thinking via codex mcp add, and runs a verification checklist end-to-end.

/mcp

