You are fully provisioned. From a control-plane perspective, Codex is detecting sequential-thinking as enabled and advertising the sequentialthinking tool. That means the MCP server is correctly registered, resolvable on PATH via npx, and the handshake is succeeding.

What to do next (operational validation + adoption)
1) Run a hard validation (force tool invocation)

In Codex, run a prompt that requires explicit step decomposition and execution gating. For example:

Use the sequentialthinking tool. Create a step-by-step plan to refactor a React app to a Bento UI layout, then output ONLY the final plan.


Success criteria:

Codex visibly invokes sequentialthinking

Output shows a structured sequential plan (not a generic paragraph)

2) Recommended ‚Äústandard operating prompt‚Äù (keeps Codex deterministic)

Use this template whenever you want predictable multi-step delivery:

Objective: <what you want>
Constraints: <stack, folders, do/don't>
Deliverables: <exact outputs>
Method: Use sequentialthinking to (1) clarify assumptions, (2) plan, (3) execute, (4) verify.
Output: Provide only the deliverables.


This reduces drift and keeps the agent in a controlled execution loop.

3) Troubleshooting matrix (if tool doesn‚Äôt fire)

If Codex doesn‚Äôt call the tool even though it‚Äôs enabled, it‚Äôs almost always because the prompt doesn‚Äôt create ‚Äútool pressure.‚Äù Fix by explicitly instructing:

‚ÄúUse the sequentialthinking tool‚Äù

‚ÄúDo not answer until the tool has produced a plan‚Äù

‚ÄúShow tool result‚Äù (if your Codex mode allows)

4) Optional: tighten governance (preferred in real projects)

If you‚Äôre using this for codebase work, pair it with a policy:

sequentialthinking for planning

then implementation phase with explicit file-level actions

then verification phase with tests/build checks

This gives you a repeatable pipeline: Plan ‚Üí Execute ‚Üí Validate.

